Question 3

3 (i)

Gender Distribution

ggplot(heights)+
  geom_bar(aes(x=sex,fill=sex))+
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent_format(scale=1/length(heights$sex),suffix=NULL))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c('pink2','blue4'),labels=c("Female","Male"))+
  labs(x="Gender",y="Proportion",title="Distribution of Gender")

Height Distribution

ggplot(heights,aes(x=height))+
  geom_histogram(aes(fill=sex),position='identity',bins=10,alpha=0.55)+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c('pink2','blue4'),labels=c("Female","Male"))+
  labs(x='Height',title='Height Distribution using histogram with 10 bins')

ggplot(heights,aes(x=height))+
  geom_histogram(aes(fill=sex),position='identity',bins=20,alpha=0.55)+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c('pink2','blue4'),labels=c("Female","Male"))+
  labs(x='Height',title='Height Distribution using histogram with 20 bins')

3 (ii)

ggplot(heights,aes(x=height,fill=!((height<=65)&(height>=55))))+
  geom_histogram(aes(y=after_stat(count / sum(count))),breaks=seq(45,85,10))+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks= seq(45,85,10))+
  scale_fill_manual(name='Heights',values = c("red3","blue4"),
                     labels = c("55-65 Heights", "Other Heights"))+
  labs(x='Height',y='Percentage',title='Percentage of Heights')

We can see that the range 55-65 contains nearly 20% of the heights.

3 (iii)

ggplot(heights,aes(x=height,fill=((height<60)|(height>78))))+

  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+
  scale_fill_manual(name='Heights',values = c("red3","steelblue"),
                     labels = c( "95% Heights","Rest"))+
  labs(x='Height',y='Percentage',title='Percentage of Heights')

Question 4

male_data=heights |> filter(sex=='Male')
dens=density(male_data$height)
d=as.data.frame(cbind(dens$x,dens$y))
ggplot(male_data,aes(x=height))+
  geom_density(fill='blue2',alpha=0.2)+
  geom_ribbon(data=d,aes(y=V2,ymin=0,ymax=V2,x=ifelse(V1>=66 & V1<=72,V1,NA)),fill='red3',alpha=0.5)+
  labs(x='Height',y='Density',title='Density of heights: Highlighting heights in the range 66-72')+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(48,84,6))

For the same data, plot and justify how is smoothed density graph different from the histogram.

ggplot(male_data,aes(x=height))+
  geom_histogram(bins=20,color='blue',fill='steelblue')+
  geom_density(aes(y=after_stat(count)*(1.9)),fill='blue',alpha=0.2)+
  labs(x='Height',y=NULL,title='Histogram and Density')

Note : In the above plot density is scaled to match with histogram.

Question 5

male_data=heights |> filter(sex=='Male') 
normal_curve=rnorm(1000,mean(male_data$height),sd(male_data$height))

ggplot(male_data)+
  geom_density(data=as.data.frame(normal_curve),aes(x=normal_curve,fill='Normal Curve'),alpha=0.1)+
  geom_density(aes(x=height,fill='Male Height Density'),alpha=0.7)+
  labs(x='Male Height',y='Density',title='Male Height Density curve',fill='Legend')

We can see that the male height data (almost) follows normal distribution.

y=male_data$height
std_dev_data=ifelse(abs(y-mean(y))<1.5*sd(y),y,NA)
x_min=min(std_dev_data,na.rm=TRUE)
x_max=max(std_dev_data,na.rm=TRUE)

dens=density(male_data$height)
d=as.data.frame(cbind(dens$x,dens$y))

ggplot(male_data)+
  geom_density(aes(x=height),fill='darkblue',alpha=0.5)+
  geom_ribbon(data=d,aes(y=V2,ymin=0,ymax=V2,x=ifelse(V1>=x_min& V1<=x_max,V1,NA)),fill='red3',alpha=0.5)+
  geom_text(aes(x=60,y=0.11,label='88% values within 1.5 standard distribution of the mean'))+
  geom_segment(aes(x=58,y=0.105,xend=66,yend=0.08),arrow = arrow())+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(50,60,x_min,70,x_max,80))+
  labs(x='Male Height',y='Density',title='Male Height Density')

Problem 6

Understanding the correlation of palmitic acid with other acids.

data("olive")
ggplot(data=olive,aes(x=palmitoleic,y=palmitic,color=region))+geom_point()+labs(title='Palmitoleic vs Palmitic',x='Palmitoleic',y='Palmitic')+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  facet_wrap(~region)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
